    "narrative_summary": "The APC c.487C>T variant is a single\u2011base substitution that converts a glutamine codon (CAG) at position 163 to a stop codon (TAG), producing a premature termination (p.Gln163*) as documented in two recent publications [PMC10471768][PMC11264515].\n\nNeither of the cited articles provides clinical classification, case reports, segregation data, or any explicit interpretation of pathogenicity for this truncating change; the variant is simply listed among other APC mutations detected in tumor sequencing panels without further annotation [PMC10471768][PMC11264515].\n\nNo functional assays or experimental studies assessing the impact of the p.Gln163* truncation on APC protein function are reported in the extracted evidence, and the articles do not present any in\u2011vitro or in\u2011vivo data related to this variant [PMC10471768][PMC11264515].\n\nSimilarly, the sources do not include population frequency data, allele counts, or computational predictions (e.g., in\u2011silico splice or missense scores) for APC c.487C>T, leaving the variant\u2019s prevalence in healthy cohorts and its predicted deleteriousness unaddressed [PMC10471768][PMC11264515].\n\nIn summary, the available evidence identifies APC c.487C>T as a nonsense mutation that would truncate the protein, a molecular consequence often associated with loss\u2011of\u2011function in tumor suppressor genes. However, because the cited studies provide no clinical, functional, population, or computational data to support a definitive classification, the pathogenicity of this variant remains uncertain and cannot be conclusively determined from the current literature.",
